{{Infobox building |name = Central Park Place |image = [[Image:Central Park Place 301 W57 St from 6th Av jeh.jpg|200px|Central Park Place]] |image_size = 250px |caption = |location = |coordinates = |status = |start_date = |completion_date = 1988 |opening = |building_type = |antenna_spire = |roof = {{convert|628|ft|m|abbr=on}} |top_floor = |floor_count = 56 |elevator_count = |cost = |floor_area = |architect = [[Davis Brody Bond]] |structural_engineer= |main_contractor = |developer = [[William Zeckendorf, Jr.|Zeckendorf]] |owner = |management = |references = <ref name="ctbuh">{{ctbuh|id=1943|fechaacceso=13 de febrero de 2016}}</ref><ref name="emporis">{{emporis|id=115499|fechaacceso=13 de febrero de 2016}}</ref> }} '''Central Park Place''' is a 56-story [[condominium]] building in [[New York City]].<ref name="ctbuh"/> The building was completed in 1988, and is located at 301 West 57th Street (between [[Eighth Avenue (Manhattan)|Eighth Avenue]] & [[Ninth Avenue (Manhattan)|Ninth Avenue]]).<ref name="emporis"/>" It is [[Tallest buildings in New York City|one of the one hundred tallest buildings in New York City]], standing at {{Convert|628|ft|m|0}} tall.
In 1987, during the construction of Central Park Place, a piece of lumber was dislodged from one of the higher floors during wind storm and hit a 37-year-old man in the head while he was walking on the east side of 8th Avenue opposite the building. He sustained massive brain trauma and died. The City of New York halted construction to investigate the incident. The builder, losing money because of the work stoppage, sued the city. The consequence of this tragedy was a new requirement that all tall building construction projects were required to place netting over any open areas to prevent the accidental loss of debris from the higher floors.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1987/06/03/nyregion/record-is-poor-at-fatality-site-on-8th-avenue.html NY Times Record is Poor at Fatality Site on 8th Avenue]</ref>{{citation needed|date=February 2016}}
The architectural firm responsible for the building is [[Davis Brody Bond]] and was developed by [[William Zeckendorf, Jr.|William Zeckendorf]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://streeteasy.com/nyc/building/central-park-place|title=Building: Central Park Place at 301 West 57th Street in Clinton|publisher=Street Easy|accessdate=14 March 2013}}</ref>
